  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Gold
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How many miles remain on the road ahead?
    The twilight deepens into dimness—
    Beyond the heavens, north wind turns the sky black,
    While in the west, the setting sun burns gold.

    The women ride their horses with such grace,
    The children know well how to mount the sheep.
    That melody—is it not "Falling Plum Blossoms"?
    Each note, each note severs the wanderer's heart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '"Falling Plum Blossoms" (落梅花曲) is a traditional Chinese tune often played on the flute, associated with melancholy and parting.'
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs the traditional motif of the traveler on an evening journey, using natural imagery and distant music to evoke the ache of separation and homesickness.
